endly error categories, such as `Unauthorized` and `Bad Request`, for a consistent response format. This should allow for a consistent response format for all errors!\n\n\n**Defining Error Maps and Handlers**\n\nI've just implemented the custom exception handlers. I've mapped HTTP status codes to user-friendly error titles such as \"Not Found\" and \"Conflict\". I've created dedicated handlers for both `HTTPException` and `RequestValidationError`, ensuring they return the unified response format. My approach also accounts for detailed validation error messages.\n\n\n**Adding Error Handlers and Tests**\n\nI'm now integrating the exception handler and preparing to test its functionality with existing tests. I'm focusing on adding the handler to `backend/app/main.py`, reviewing the imports, and considering if other backend files need changes. Before moving forward, I'll review `backend/app/api/routes/projects.py` for possible pagination needs, as well. I'm prioritizing ensuring compatibility with the current test suite.\n\n\n**Reviewing `projects.py` Again**\n\nI'm now revisiting `backend/app/api/routes/projects.py`. I'm taking another look at lines 1-44 to ensure I haven't missed anything regarding the exception handler implementation or pagination. I'm focusing on potential interactions between the new exception handling and the existing project listing functionality.\n\n\n**Updating Project Listing Endpoint**\n\nI'm now integrating pagination into the project listing endpoint in `backend/app/api/routes/projects.py`, adding `limit` and `offset` parameters for a more efficient and user-friendly experience. I'm focusing on modifying the existing `list_projects` method to accept these parameters and implement the appropriate slicing of the query results. I'm also ensuring that the new implementation aligns with the defined role-based access control logic to maintain data security.\n\n\n**Enhancing Pagination Logic**\n\nI'm now integrating enhanced pagination within `bac