{"ts":"2026-06-27T16:56:03.138Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Celebrating Test Successes**\n\nFantastic! I'm thrilled to report that all FastAPI tests have passed flawlessly, covering security, RBAC, smoke tests, and the client CRUD API. I am moving on to ensure API consistency and pagination implementation within Next.js.\n\n\n**Listing API Endpoints**\n\nI've begun listing our API endpoints to check what we've got. I've documented these: `projects`, `users`, `governance`, `documents`, `invoices`, `support`, and `ai-operations`. I'm going to focus on the GET method in `app/api/v1/projects/route.ts` next to understand its implementation and RBAC policy. I've re-read the code for the GET method, including lines 34-102.\n\n\n**Analyzing GET Parameters**\n\nI'm now examining the GET request parameters within the `/api/v1/projects/route.ts` file, specifically how filters like 'phase', 'status', 'health', 'owner', and 'search' are handled. I've noted the RBAC policy logic which filters projects based on the caller's role, and client association. Further, I've seen how the client ID is used to enforce access control.\n\n\n**Implementing Pagination Logic**\n\nI'm now implementing pagination for the `/api/v1/projects/route.ts` GET method. I'm modifying the code to accept `limit` and `offset` (or `skip`) query parameters for pagination. I am focused on validating these parameters, ensuring they are integers and handling potential errors gracefully. I need to make the response paginated, which also covers RBAC and search filters.\n\n\n"}}
